{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 2. Analyse the structure and functions provided by the kernel of an OS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The kernel is a collection of services/functions that make up the core of the OS. They offer a level of abstraction from the hardware of the computer. This abstraction is useful because code can be written to run on an operating system rather than on a specific platform, and then it will run on any platform which supports that operating system.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The main components of the kernel are:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab device drivers\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab file system manager\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab process management\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab memory management\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab network services\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The device drivers are used to accommodate I/O devices that vary considerably in how and how fast they communicate with the OS. They hide low-level details of these devices from the user and provide a uniform method of interaction with devices.\par}
