{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 49. How does a device driver work?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A device driver is a piece of software that extends the kernel (runs with kernel privileges). It interacts with processes and with the hardware device controller.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two control flows within the driver:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab the first is executed on behalf of a process requesting a service\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab a process requests an I/O service and passes parameters to the driver\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab the driver translates these parameters into controller parameters, which it delivers to the device controller\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab the second responds to interrupts\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab the controller issues an interrupt\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab the driver handles the interrupt, possibly passing information back to the relevant processes\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 These two control flows share a common data structure. As the first flow can be interrupted, the two must co-ordinate their access to a shared request queue. The two flows use mutual exclusion techniques to prevent corruption of the queue.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 50. Explain the concept of driver families.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Driver families provide a level of abstraction that accommodates all devices of the same type.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A driver becomes a member of a family through inheritance, and inherits the data structures and behaviours common to the family. It can use these to, for example, scan the SCSI bus as the SCSI Parallel family defines.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A driver will also implement member functions that the family invokes.\par}
